WEBVTT

00:04.171 --> 00:07.174
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:07.174 --> 00:14.181
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.766 --> 00:18.810
‐ My name is John Summerhill.
I have probably made

00:18.810 --> 00:21.813
about 15 knives
from start to finish.

00:21.813 --> 00:24.066
I am a high school
assistant principal,

00:24.066 --> 00:25.776
<i>so every day is an adventure.</i>

00:25.776 --> 00:27.653
<i>I'm ready for anything</i>
<i>that's coming at me,</i>

00:27.653 --> 00:30.656
and I look forward to trying
to adapt and beat those odds.

00:31.573 --> 00:33.534
<i>‐ My name is Daniel Ivano.</i>

00:33.534 --> 00:36.036
I got into bladesmithing
when I went

00:36.036 --> 00:38.205
to the Renaissance festival
and then realized

00:38.205 --> 00:40.123
there were guys
that were still doing it.

00:40.123 --> 00:44.044
I'm here to have fun,
but I'm also here to win.

00:44.044 --> 00:46.046
<i>‐ My name's Mike Vannoy.</i>

00:46.046 --> 00:47.506
I'm a full‐time farrier

00:47.506 --> 00:49.424
<i>and a part‐time bladesmith.</i>

00:49.424 --> 00:51.843
I'm used to dealing
with the unknown,

00:51.843 --> 00:53.679
because when I go to a new barn
in the morning,

00:53.679 --> 00:55.597
<i>you just never know</i>

00:55.597 --> 00:57.724
<i>how the horse is gonna react</i>
<i>to what you're doing.</i>

00:57.724 --> 01:00.227
You just never know
what's gonna happen.

01:00.227 --> 01:03.063
‐ My name is Curtis Shaw.
I'm a maintenance mechanic.

01:03.063 --> 01:05.649
<i>I work on equipment</i>
<i>that's the size of a house,</i>

01:05.649 --> 01:08.318
and bladesmithing
is relaxing to me.

01:08.318 --> 01:10.612
<i>I am a huge</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" fan,</i>

01:10.612 --> 01:13.907
and I would love to bring home
a "Forged in Fire" title.

01:13.907 --> 01:15.701
Plus the $10,000 check.

01:15.701 --> 01:17.828
[laughs]

01:17.828 --> 01:20.289
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:20.289 --> 01:21.915
Each of you is here to engage
in three rounds

01:21.915 --> 01:24.209
of timed edged weapon‐making
competition

01:24.209 --> 01:26.003
designed to test
every aspect of your skills

01:26.003 --> 01:27.462
and push you
to your limits,

01:27.462 --> 01:29.506
all in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:29.506 --> 01:30.882
who will tell us which of you

01:30.882 --> 01:32.301
is our next
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:32.301 --> 01:34.886
leaving here with a check
for $10,000.

01:34.886 --> 01:36.763
So let's go ahead and meet
your judges now.

01:36.763 --> 01:39.558
Up first, two‐time
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:39.558 --> 01:41.268
Ben Abbott.

01:41.268 --> 01:44.229
Historic weapons re‐creation
specialist David Baker.

01:44.229 --> 01:47.941
And last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:47.941 --> 01:49.192
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:49.192 --> 01:50.360
All right, I hope that you're

01:50.360 --> 01:51.695
ready to spring into action.

01:51.695 --> 01:53.947
This is your first challenge.

01:53.947 --> 01:55.490
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:55.490 --> 01:57.367
You are going to engage in

01:57.367 --> 01:58.910
the little spring,
big spring challenge.

01:58.910 --> 02:00.662
You must combine at least

02:00.662 --> 02:03.415
three small springs with
a section of the large spring

02:03.415 --> 02:06.084
to forge a billet,
from which you will make

02:06.084 --> 02:07.919
a signature blade
in your signature style

02:07.919 --> 02:09.796
that falls within
the following parameters:

02:09.796 --> 02:11.214
<i>the length of your blade</i>

02:11.214 --> 02:12.507
<i>must fall between</i>

02:12.507 --> 02:14.301
<i>11 and 14 inches.</i>

02:14.301 --> 02:16.511
<i>The overall length must not</i>
<i>exceed 22 inches,</i>

02:16.511 --> 02:18.639
and you must acid‐etch
your blades

02:18.639 --> 02:20.682
before the end of the round.

02:20.682 --> 02:22.601
<i>‐ As I'm looking</i>
<i>at the springs,</i>

02:22.601 --> 02:24.519
<i>I'm starting to sweat already.</i>

02:24.519 --> 02:27.689
I'm becoming more nervous than
I thought I was going to be.

02:27.689 --> 02:30.150
‐ In round two, you'll attach
handles to those blades

02:30.150 --> 02:32.611
so that we can test them
for strength and durability

02:32.611 --> 02:34.571
in a pipe split

02:34.571 --> 02:37.491
and for edge retention
in a fish slice.

02:37.491 --> 02:40.035
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your 10‐minute design window

02:40.035 --> 02:42.454
starts now.

02:42.454 --> 02:45.791
All right, so each of these
guys has to take

02:45.791 --> 02:47.417
three smaller springs,

02:47.417 --> 02:49.419
combine it
with the larger spring.

02:49.419 --> 02:50.962
How would you do it?

02:50.962 --> 02:53.507
‐ I'd probably cut the springs
into rings,

02:53.507 --> 02:55.425
cut the big spring
into discs‐‐‐

02:55.425 --> 02:56.927
toss 'em all in a can.

02:56.927 --> 02:58.428
‐ So canister Damascus
is the way to go.

02:58.428 --> 03:00.347
‐ But one of the biggest
concerns that I have

03:00.347 --> 03:01.973
is the amount of steel
they'll need

03:01.973 --> 03:03.725
to hit that parameter.

03:03.725 --> 03:04.935
‐ It's a lot of metal.

03:04.935 --> 03:07.688
<i>‐ I'm designing a mix between</i>

03:07.688 --> 03:10.357
a camp knife and a seax...

03:10.357 --> 03:13.902
<i>the seax is very much meant</i>
<i>for chopping</i>

03:13.902 --> 03:16.238
<i>and for slicing.</i>

03:16.238 --> 03:19.658
<i>Making blades</i>
<i>is a very relaxing hobby.</i>

03:19.658 --> 03:21.576
You can take out
a lot of your frustration

03:21.576 --> 03:24.830
<i>on the metal, and you're</i>
<i>creating something</i>

03:24.830 --> 03:27.207
from nothing, almost.

03:27.207 --> 03:28.708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:28.708 --> 03:30.293
<i>‐ I started making blades</i>

03:30.293 --> 03:32.963
not long after I started
shoeing horses,

03:32.963 --> 03:36.341
<i>mainly using old rasps</i>
<i>or files.</i>

03:36.341 --> 03:40.387
<i>My design</i>
<i>is a camp knife/chopper</i>

03:40.387 --> 03:42.639
<i>with a slightly recurved</i>
<i>blade.</i>

03:42.639 --> 03:45.767
<i>It'll be a heavy blade</i>
<i>with some heft to it</i>

03:45.767 --> 03:48.353
<i>that'll just hold up well.</i>

03:48.353 --> 03:51.314
<i>‐ I'm wearing a kilt today</i>
<i>because I am Scottish</i>

03:51.314 --> 03:55.527
and English, and I'm
representing my background.

03:55.527 --> 03:57.529
‐ John, what subject
do you teach in school?

03:57.529 --> 03:59.906
‐ I'm an assistant principal.
‐ Oh, nice.

03:59.906 --> 04:01.700
‐ He teaches intimidation.
‐ Yes.

04:01.700 --> 04:03.618
‐ He can just‐‐
stay in school.

04:03.618 --> 04:07.080
<i>‐ My plan is to make</i>
<i>a large camp knife.</i>

04:07.080 --> 04:09.624
<i>It will be thick; it'll be</i>
<i>able to handle cutting through</i>

04:09.624 --> 04:12.002
<i>some hard surfaces,</i>
<i>but at the same time</i>

04:12.002 --> 04:14.713
<i>slice through something thin.</i>

04:14.713 --> 04:16.631
<i>‐ I want to win</i>
<i>this competition</i>

04:16.631 --> 04:18.675
because this is
my wife's birthday.

04:18.675 --> 04:21.011
<i>My wife's</i>
<i>my biggest cheerleader.</i>

04:21.011 --> 04:22.846
<i>I'm choosing</i>
<i>the full tang bowie</i>

04:22.846 --> 04:25.015
<i>because it is a strong design,</i>

04:25.015 --> 04:26.683
<i>it's a quick design,</i>

04:26.683 --> 04:28.685
<i>and I think</i>
<i>in this competition,</i>

04:28.685 --> 04:30.854
<i>it would be</i>
<i>a great competitor.</i>

04:30.854 --> 04:32.522
<i>This is gonna be very tough.</i>

04:32.522 --> 04:34.858
<i>Getting a blade completed in</i>
<i>three hours‐‐</i>

04:34.858 --> 04:37.360
<i>Acid‐etched,</i>
<i>heat‐treated?</i>

04:37.360 --> 04:38.904
I don't know if I can do that.

04:38.904 --> 04:40.864
‐ Bladesmiths, your design
period is closed.

04:40.864 --> 04:43.158
Your three‐hour forge time
starts... now.

04:43.158 --> 04:44.493
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:44.493 --> 04:45.577
‐ We know that they're gonna
whittle down

04:45.577 --> 04:46.912
that big coil spring,

04:46.912 --> 04:48.997
just‐‐he don't need
all of that.

04:48.997 --> 04:51.541
‐ Just a piece about that big,
dropped in the middle,

04:51.541 --> 04:53.752
put springs on either side
of it‐‐

04:53.752 --> 04:55.712
fill it with the powder.

04:55.712 --> 04:58.423
You and I both know that if you
don't pack that powder in,

04:58.423 --> 04:59.758
you're gonna wind up
with voids,

04:59.758 --> 05:02.177
cold shuts,
not welding...

05:02.177 --> 05:03.762
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:03.762 --> 05:05.138
‐ Curtis using
the Liquid Paper,

05:05.138 --> 05:08.517
planning to peel
that soft metal can

05:08.517 --> 05:10.936
off of that
hardened steel core.

05:10.936 --> 05:14.648
‐ My game plan is to add in
the smaller springs,

05:14.648 --> 05:18.443
put my powdered metal,
my pieces of coil spring in‐‐

05:18.443 --> 05:20.403
it's easy.

05:20.403 --> 05:22.113
<i>I need to weld a little</i>
<i>on my can,</i>

05:22.113 --> 05:24.032
<i>get it ready to put</i>
<i>in the forge.</i>

05:24.032 --> 05:25.575
Things are going...

05:25.575 --> 05:26.618
fairly well.

05:26.618 --> 05:28.578
Awww!

05:28.578 --> 05:31.081
That canister's ruined.

05:31.081 --> 05:32.999
One side of my can
wasn't fully welded,

05:32.999 --> 05:34.876
and when I moved the can,

05:34.876 --> 05:36.753
<i>some of my powder fell out.</i>

05:36.753 --> 05:38.296
Gonna have to start over.

05:38.296 --> 05:41.091
<i>The can is no longer</i>
<i>tightly packed,</i>

05:41.091 --> 05:44.928
<i>and I knew that the billet was</i>
<i>not gonna forge weld properly.</i>

05:44.928 --> 05:47.848
Things are not going my way.

05:47.848 --> 05:49.641
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:49.641 --> 05:51.810
‐ I know first thing I need
to do is cut off two pieces

05:51.810 --> 05:55.522
of my large coil.

05:55.522 --> 05:58.149
‐ Ha! Mike burned a hole
in his shirt.

05:58.149 --> 06:01.361
‐ 'Cause I had the angle
grinder sparks facing me,

06:01.361 --> 06:03.196
I was kinda worried
about spraying sparks

06:03.196 --> 06:04.656
on everybody else,

06:04.656 --> 06:07.325
but I wasn't so worried
about myself.

06:07.325 --> 06:09.160
‐ Mike! You all right?

06:09.160 --> 06:10.871
‐ Yeah, I'm all right.

06:10.871 --> 06:13.206
As soon as this round's over,
I have an extra shirt

06:13.206 --> 06:16.334
to change into, so I should
be okay.

06:16.334 --> 06:19.004
‐ So Mike's just come away
from the pantry

06:19.004 --> 06:20.964
with one of our canisters.

06:20.964 --> 06:23.884
<i>‐ When you do a canister weld,</i>
<i>you want to make sure</i>

06:23.884 --> 06:26.511
<i>there's no air pockets</i>
<i>in the canister,</i>

06:26.511 --> 06:30.056
so you want to fill the whole
canister with steel.

06:30.056 --> 06:32.434
‐ Here's what I like about
what Mike's doing,

06:32.434 --> 06:34.311
is he doesn't have any
white‐out in that can.

06:34.311 --> 06:37.147
So by not doing that,
we know that entire piece

06:37.147 --> 06:38.857
will weld into one piece
of metal.

06:38.857 --> 06:40.650
Won't have to cut the can off‐‐

06:40.650 --> 06:42.152
can get to the grinding
a lot quicker.

06:42.152 --> 06:44.613
‐ I'm gonna leave the can on.

06:44.613 --> 06:46.489
With going through
that pipe chop,

06:46.489 --> 06:48.992
I want a little bit
of soft steel on the spine,

06:48.992 --> 06:51.244
and I think that'll
work out good.

06:51.244 --> 06:55.206
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:55.206 --> 06:57.375
‐ I've got a piece
of big spring.

06:57.375 --> 07:00.962
<i>I've got little springs</i>
<i>and some angle iron.</i>

07:00.962 --> 07:03.340
<i>And now, I just need</i>
<i>to flatten them out.</i>

07:03.340 --> 07:05.467
‐ Daniel, he's doing
his own thing.

07:05.467 --> 07:07.344
I don't see a can
over at his station.

07:07.344 --> 07:11.264
‐ I wonder if Daniel is gonna
go for some kind of San Mai.

07:11.264 --> 07:12.390
<i>I'd love it.</i>

07:12.390 --> 07:13.516
<i>‐ I'm gonna try and create,</i>

07:13.516 --> 07:15.435
<i>like, a layered billet</i>

07:15.435 --> 07:18.897
with the smaller springs
and the mild steel.

07:18.897 --> 07:20.815
<i>Got everything flattened out.</i>

07:20.815 --> 07:23.860
Now I've just got to weld it
all together.

07:23.860 --> 07:26.780
I'm having the hardest time
stacking it

07:26.780 --> 07:28.490
<i>and keeping it stacked,</i>

07:28.490 --> 07:30.033
<i>and I realize</i>

07:30.033 --> 07:31.576
I'm burning minutes here.

07:34.120 --> 07:38.124
I decide I'm gonna do
canister Damascus.

07:40.293 --> 07:41.628
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:41.628 --> 07:42.712
<i>‐ I cleaned the metal up.</i>

07:42.712 --> 07:44.255
<i>I put white‐out in.</i>

07:44.255 --> 07:46.132
Got her in the forge.
Heating it up.

07:46.132 --> 07:48.176
<i>Once I got about</i>
<i>15 minutes in,</i>

07:48.176 --> 07:50.637
I'm good to go
with pulling that out.

07:50.637 --> 07:54.849
‐ Now John's taking a very hot
billet over to the press.

07:54.849 --> 07:56.893
<i>‐ As I'm setting the welds,</i>
<i>I'm feeling pretty good.</i>

07:56.893 --> 07:58.812
<i>I don't have anything</i>
<i>falling apart.</i>

07:58.812 --> 08:01.356
It is doing exactly what it's
supposed to be doing.

08:01.356 --> 08:02.482
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:02.482 --> 08:03.900
‐ Look at John over here.

08:03.900 --> 08:06.403
He's got a‐‐basically
a block of Velveeta

08:06.403 --> 08:08.488
locked into a vice
over there.

08:08.488 --> 08:11.241
And he's hogging it away
with that angle grinder,

08:11.241 --> 08:14.452
looking to peel that can.

08:14.452 --> 08:16.371
<i>‐ The only thing that I'm</i>
<i>nervous about is if</i>

08:16.371 --> 08:19.124
I can't get the canister off

08:19.124 --> 08:21.000
<i>of the material inside.</i>

08:21.000 --> 08:22.669
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:22.669 --> 08:24.087
And finally...

08:24.087 --> 08:25.213
[steel clinks]

08:25.213 --> 08:26.923
Ha, ha!

08:26.923 --> 08:28.591
The billet falls to the ground,

08:28.591 --> 08:30.635
and I have defeated
the canister.

08:30.635 --> 08:32.512
‐ There you go!
Look at that.

08:32.512 --> 08:35.765
John's got
a billet out of that box.

08:35.765 --> 08:37.600
‐ Trophy!

08:37.600 --> 08:38.977
‐ Bladesmiths!

08:38.977 --> 08:40.937
One hour has elapsed!

08:40.937 --> 08:42.814
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:42.814 --> 08:45.150
<i>‐ My billet</i>
<i>is forged‐welded solid</i>

08:45.150 --> 08:47.861
into one solid piece of steel.

08:47.861 --> 08:51.239
Now I'm gonna draw it out
so I can establish a tang...

08:51.239 --> 08:52.741
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:52.741 --> 08:56.578
And actually forge a point
into the knife.

08:56.578 --> 08:59.456
‐ Mike's got a handle coming
along; he's got a blade shape.

08:59.456 --> 09:02.751
<i>‐ I need to take some of</i>
<i>the thickness out of my blade.</i>

09:02.751 --> 09:05.295
I have to be careful with that,
because I left my canister

09:05.295 --> 09:07.005
on the knife,

09:07.005 --> 09:08.840
<i>so I don't want to thin it out</i>
<i>too much</i>

09:08.840 --> 09:10.717
<i>and not have</i>
<i>enough hardenable steel</i>

09:10.717 --> 09:11.760
<i>in the center.</i>

09:11.760 --> 09:15.221
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:15.221 --> 09:17.891
‐ I've never done
canister Damascus before.

09:17.891 --> 09:20.477
‐ Look at that rocket that
Daniel is putting

09:20.477 --> 09:22.145
into his forge right now!

09:22.145 --> 09:23.813
‐ That's just powder
on the outside of the can.

09:23.813 --> 09:25.774
<i>‐ The clock is ticking away,</i>

09:25.774 --> 09:28.526
and I know it's gonna
take a while

09:28.526 --> 09:31.071
to make this canister Damascus.

09:31.071 --> 09:32.489
Mike, you think it's
hot enough?

09:32.489 --> 09:33.865
I can't tell.

09:33.865 --> 09:35.200
‐ When you think
it's hot enough,

09:35.200 --> 09:37.077
wait another minute
or two.

09:37.077 --> 09:38.119
[laughs]

09:38.119 --> 09:39.496
‐ Some good advice.

09:39.496 --> 09:42.791
And now I've gotta go
forge‐weld it.

09:42.791 --> 09:45.210
<i>I start to press it together,</i>

09:45.210 --> 09:46.878
and it just starts
to fall apart.

09:50.090 --> 09:53.176
‐ Oh, my God, the entire top
of the can just peeled off.

09:53.176 --> 09:56.179
<i>‐ This point,</i>
<i>I'm kind of panicking.</i>

09:56.179 --> 09:57.847
Damn it.

09:57.847 --> 10:00.100
‐ He's just shoved
that lidless coffin

10:00.100 --> 10:01.976
back into the forge.

10:01.976 --> 10:04.813
‐ From what I know,
with canister Damascus,

10:04.813 --> 10:07.941
you usually want to take
the canister off anyway,

10:07.941 --> 10:10.151
so... one less step.

10:10.151 --> 10:13.947
‐ If Daniel had to put any kind
of flux in that canoe,

10:13.947 --> 10:15.824
you know, maybe he'd have
a shot at getting that stuff

10:15.824 --> 10:17.450
to stick.

10:17.450 --> 10:19.285
<i>‐ I'm hoping to salvage</i>
<i>something from it.</i>

10:19.285 --> 10:21.412
<i>Here's to hoping.</i>

10:21.412 --> 10:22.872
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:22.872 --> 10:24.791
‐ We've got Curtis,
who's a little bit behind

10:24.791 --> 10:27.168
the power curve compared
to the other smiths.

10:27.168 --> 10:29.796
<i>‐ I've spent a whole lot</i>
<i>of time putting together</i>

10:29.796 --> 10:32.382
<i>a canoe that I cannot use.</i>

10:32.382 --> 10:35.760
<i>So I have to move on</i>
<i>to another canoe.</i>

10:35.760 --> 10:37.637
Hopefully this time,
it'll come out.

10:37.637 --> 10:39.722
Starting to get
at the right temperature.

10:39.722 --> 10:43.810
I put it in the press,
pressed it a couple times...

10:43.810 --> 10:45.812
‐ Curtis is grinding
the can off.

10:45.812 --> 10:47.230
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:47.230 --> 10:49.858
He only made one hot run
on the press.

10:49.858 --> 10:53.611
I don't know how there could be
a truly solid weld in it.

10:53.611 --> 10:55.697
‐ Yeah, it's way too soon
to be cutting that can off.

10:55.697 --> 10:58.908
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:58.908 --> 11:00.869
‐ As I'm removing the canister,
I noticed

11:00.869 --> 11:02.537
<i>that there was chunks</i>
<i>of billet falling out,</i>

11:02.537 --> 11:05.123
so I know at that moment,
there's no saving it.

11:05.123 --> 11:06.499
It's just garbage.

11:06.499 --> 11:08.334
[groans]

11:08.334 --> 11:12.172
‐ Oh, man, you can just see
inside, it's just busted up.

11:12.172 --> 11:13.923
‐ I don't think it had time
to soak enough,

11:13.923 --> 11:15.717
so the powder just came apart

11:15.717 --> 11:17.760
inside the canister,
basically.

11:17.760 --> 11:19.929
<i>Hour and a half has went by</i>
<i>on the clock.</i>

11:19.929 --> 11:22.182
I figure I have enough time
to make a third can.

11:22.182 --> 11:24.976
<i>This is just not my day.</i>

11:24.976 --> 11:26.728
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:26.728 --> 11:29.314
<i>‐ I start drawing out</i>
<i>the billet.</i>

11:29.314 --> 11:31.024
It's looking good.

11:31.024 --> 11:33.276
Then I look a little closer,

11:33.276 --> 11:36.070
<i>and I start to see</i>
<i>little, tiny cracks.</i>

11:36.070 --> 11:38.448
Now I've got to make a decision
at this point

11:38.448 --> 11:40.158
<i>how I'm gonna solve</i>
<i>this issue.</i>

11:40.158 --> 11:41.910
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:41.910 --> 11:44.370
<i>My first priority here</i>
<i>is to fill those gaps</i>

11:44.370 --> 11:46.915
so that the blade
is structurally sound.

11:46.915 --> 11:48.917
‐ By welding those cracks up,

11:48.917 --> 11:51.920
he's got that blade back up
to welding temperature

11:51.920 --> 11:53.254
and started hitting the edge,

11:53.254 --> 11:54.631
and forging doubles it.

11:54.631 --> 11:56.341
‐ Okay.
‐ Hopefully, he's kind of

11:56.341 --> 11:58.593
forge‐welding some of those
cracks back together.

11:58.593 --> 12:00.053
‐ I'm hoping to see
it's a surface

12:00.053 --> 12:01.763
and I got a solid billet
underneath,

12:01.763 --> 12:04.265
and then I can just start
shaping and grinding.

12:04.265 --> 12:05.975
‐ Bladesmiths!

12:05.975 --> 12:07.936
Two hours has elapsed.

12:07.936 --> 12:10.396
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:10.396 --> 12:12.815
‐ This is my third canister.
I need this one.

12:12.815 --> 12:15.318
This time, I'm going to use
an upright canister

12:15.318 --> 12:16.694
<i>versus the canoe.</i>

12:16.694 --> 12:18.655
My pattern probably won't be
as nice,

12:18.655 --> 12:20.448
but it should go quicker.

12:20.448 --> 12:23.618
‐ It'll be the first time
in "Forged in Fire" history

12:23.618 --> 12:26.079
that a smith has gone
for a third can,

12:26.079 --> 12:28.122
and if he pulls this off,
he'll be a legend.

12:28.122 --> 12:29.916
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:29.916 --> 12:32.418
Right now, all eyes on Curtis.

12:32.418 --> 12:36.089
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:36.089 --> 12:37.257
‐ Come on, Curtis.

12:39.759 --> 12:41.261
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:41.261 --> 12:43.346
‐ Aw, no, Curtis.
Come on, man.

12:43.346 --> 12:45.056
‐ Oh no, oh no, oh no.

12:45.056 --> 12:47.100
<i>Curtis's face says it all.</i>

12:47.100 --> 12:49.435
‐ The canister forge‐welded
into the billet.

12:49.435 --> 12:51.646
<i>Trying to get the canister</i>
<i>off of it.</i>

12:51.646 --> 12:53.106
<i>That did not work.</i>

12:53.106 --> 12:55.441
I figure, try one more time.

12:55.441 --> 12:57.277
‐ Come on, Curtis,
you got it, baby.

12:57.277 --> 12:58.528
You got it.

12:58.528 --> 12:59.946
‐ I came here to compete,

12:59.946 --> 13:01.447
and I'm gonna
turn something in.

13:01.447 --> 13:05.785
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:05.785 --> 13:08.037
<i>‐ If I quench,</i>
<i>and there's no cracking,</i>

13:08.037 --> 13:11.291
<i>I know my welds</i>
<i>are good and solid.</i>

13:11.291 --> 13:12.625
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:12.625 --> 13:13.918
‐ Michael just quenched
his blade.

13:13.918 --> 13:15.628
‐ First quenched blade.

13:15.628 --> 13:17.338
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:17.338 --> 13:19.507
<i>File's blading into</i>
<i>the blade a little bit,</i>

13:19.507 --> 13:21.551
so I know it's not
completely hardened

13:21.551 --> 13:23.344
the way I'd like it to be.

13:23.344 --> 13:27.015
Hate to quench again,
but I don't quite trust it.

13:27.015 --> 13:30.184
Not quite sure if it's because

13:30.184 --> 13:34.230
there's some mild steel left
from the canister

13:34.230 --> 13:36.316
<i>or if my steel</i>
<i>just didn't harden,</i>

13:36.316 --> 13:38.318
<i>and that could be</i>
<i>a real problem.</i>

13:38.318 --> 13:40.820
‐ Mike, he's the only one
of our smiths

13:40.820 --> 13:43.531
that did not attempt
to peel the can.

13:43.531 --> 13:47.410
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:47.410 --> 13:49.370
<i>‐ Quenched a second time,</i>
<i>and I pull it out‐‐</i>

13:49.370 --> 13:51.581
it does seem harder
than the first time,

13:51.581 --> 13:53.499
<i>so I think I'm good.</i>

13:53.499 --> 13:55.752
With the time remaining, I'm
gonna clean up the whole blade

13:55.752 --> 13:57.587
so that I can acid‐etch.

13:57.587 --> 14:00.256
‐ We are gonna want to see
those blades acid‐etched.

14:00.256 --> 14:03.426
It's gonna tell us exactly
where the mild steel is

14:03.426 --> 14:05.136
compared to the hardened steel.

14:05.136 --> 14:09.515
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:09.515 --> 14:13.144
John has just quenched
his blade as well.

14:13.144 --> 14:15.188
<i>‐ I'm really nervous</i>
<i>at this point whether or not</i>

14:15.188 --> 14:17.774
I'm gonna produce
a hardened blade.

14:17.774 --> 14:19.358
‐ John's blade
doesn't seem hard at all.

14:19.358 --> 14:20.860
‐ The hard stuff
in the blade

14:20.860 --> 14:23.154
it doesn't finish until near
room‐temperature.

14:23.154 --> 14:24.864
You got to give it time
to do its thing

14:24.864 --> 14:27.617
instead of throwing it back
into the forge again.

14:27.617 --> 14:31.245
‐ I know that every time you
heat it up and you quench it,

14:31.245 --> 14:33.039
<i>you run the risk of making it</i>
<i>more brittle,</i>

14:33.039 --> 14:34.665
but I've got to turn in
a hardened blade.

14:34.665 --> 14:38.461
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:38.461 --> 14:41.547
I pull the blade out of the
quench, and I let it cool off.

14:41.547 --> 14:43.299
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:43.299 --> 14:45.093
<i>I'm fairly confident</i>
<i>at this point</i>

14:45.093 --> 14:47.595
I've got a pretty hard blade.

14:47.595 --> 14:49.430
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:49.430 --> 14:51.057
‐ You got to give it
to Daniel, though.

14:51.057 --> 14:54.060
He had a can that was
falling apart.

14:54.060 --> 14:56.604
Somehow, he managed
to get that thing

14:56.604 --> 14:58.898
welded into something that
looks somewhat solid.

14:58.898 --> 15:01.150
<i>‐ When so much time is spent</i>

15:01.150 --> 15:03.152
<i>on trying to get</i>
<i>a workable billet,</i>

15:03.152 --> 15:05.446
I need to shape my blade fast.

15:05.446 --> 15:07.365
‐ Ten minutes!

15:07.365 --> 15:08.616
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:08.616 --> 15:10.201
‐ I'm playing a dangerous game

15:10.201 --> 15:11.911
of cat and mouse
with the clock.

15:11.911 --> 15:13.788
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:13.788 --> 15:16.082
<i>‐ At this moment,</i>
<i>it's not making parameters.</i>

15:16.082 --> 15:17.792
It's just turning in something.

15:17.792 --> 15:19.836
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths!

15:19.836 --> 15:23.089
‐ That's it.
I need to go heat‐treat it.

15:23.089 --> 15:25.591
I'm only gonna get one shot
at this quench.

15:25.591 --> 15:27.468
I have no room for error.

15:27.468 --> 15:29.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:29.303 --> 15:31.055
‐ There he goes.
Daniel in that quench.

15:31.055 --> 15:33.099
‐ Leave it in.

15:33.099 --> 15:35.601
‐ I don't have time
to pile‐check it.

15:35.601 --> 15:37.854
I don't have time
to clean it up.

15:37.854 --> 15:40.356
<i>I still have to etch it.</i>

15:40.356 --> 15:42.150
‐ I've got a lot of pride,
and quitting

15:42.150 --> 15:43.901
is not in my vocabulary.

15:43.901 --> 15:45.486
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:45.486 --> 15:47.697
‐ Five! Four!

15:47.697 --> 15:50.700
Three! Two! One!

15:50.700 --> 15:52.451
Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing!

15:52.451 --> 15:54.537
Pull your blade out
of the acid etch!

15:54.537 --> 15:58.124
This first round of competition
is over.

15:58.124 --> 15:59.876
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:59.876 --> 16:01.586
<i>‐ This is probably</i>
<i>one of the ugliest things</i>

16:01.586 --> 16:02.962
<i>I've ever made,</i>

16:02.962 --> 16:06.591
but I finished
within parameters.

16:06.591 --> 16:08.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:08.301 --> 16:11.554
‐ Bladesmiths, the three hours
in round one has elapsed.

16:11.554 --> 16:14.015
Now it's time for the judges
to take a closer look

16:14.015 --> 16:15.057
at what you've done.

16:15.057 --> 16:16.559
John, you're up first.

16:16.559 --> 16:18.477
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:18.477 --> 16:20.354
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:20.354 --> 16:22.481
<i>‐ Well, John, I like the</i>
<i>overall profile of your blade.</i>

16:22.481 --> 16:25.151
Got, still, a whole lot
of mass to it.

16:25.151 --> 16:27.361
Um, can use a lot
of grinding still.

16:27.361 --> 16:29.530
The big thing for me
is the extra inch,

16:29.530 --> 16:30.990
inch and a half of handle here.

16:30.990 --> 16:34.327
It'll be interesting
to see, if you move forward,

16:34.327 --> 16:36.204
how you're gonna deal
with the shape of it.

16:36.204 --> 16:38.873
All in all, well done.
‐ Thank you.

16:38.873 --> 16:41.000
‐ All right, Daniel,
you're up next.

16:41.000 --> 16:42.627
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:42.627 --> 16:44.253
<i>‐ Lot of question marks.</i>

16:44.253 --> 16:45.588
<i>When you start grinding</i>
<i>on this,</i>

16:45.588 --> 16:47.590
it's gonna be
interesting to see

16:47.590 --> 16:49.383
what steel's what on this.

16:49.383 --> 16:51.427
You know, a blade with
mild steel on the edge

16:51.427 --> 16:54.263
is not gonna do very well
in the tests.

16:54.263 --> 16:57.099
But I got to give you props
for making it stick together.

16:57.099 --> 16:59.393
I didn't think it
was gonna happen.

16:59.393 --> 17:01.229
Good job.

17:01.229 --> 17:03.856
‐ Mike, please present
your blade to the judges.

17:03.856 --> 17:05.650
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:05.650 --> 17:08.402
<i>‐ First off, the steel</i>
<i>is really good.</i>

17:08.402 --> 17:10.529
But the handle is
a little narrow here

17:10.529 --> 17:12.073
at the pointer finger.

17:12.073 --> 17:14.283
I kinda find myself wishing

17:14.283 --> 17:16.535
that there was a little more
meat there.

17:16.535 --> 17:19.914
There's a pretty decided warp

17:19.914 --> 17:21.666
to the blade, but all in all,

17:21.666 --> 17:23.876
that's a very solid piece.

17:23.876 --> 17:25.628
Well done.

17:25.628 --> 17:28.547
‐ Thank you.

17:28.547 --> 17:31.676
‐ All right, Curtis,
we've never had anybody attempt

17:31.676 --> 17:33.094
three cans before.

17:33.094 --> 17:34.387
The steel that you have
doesn't meet

17:34.387 --> 17:35.972
any of our parameters.

17:35.972 --> 17:37.807
I'm gonna turn you over
to Doug.

17:37.807 --> 17:39.433
‐ Curtis, as you can see,

17:39.433 --> 17:41.811
forging in a timed competition
is always hard.

17:41.811 --> 17:43.771
There's a big difference
between quitting

17:43.771 --> 17:45.398
and losing.

17:45.398 --> 17:47.567
You, sir, did not quit.
‐ Thank you.

17:47.567 --> 17:50.236
‐ Well, Curtis, you can leave
that steel on the table.

17:50.236 --> 17:51.988
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:51.988 --> 17:53.573
<i>‐ Ultimately, I didn't have</i>
<i>a knife.</i>

17:53.573 --> 17:55.408
<i>I turned in a spring,</i>

17:55.408 --> 17:57.118
<i>and that's why</i>
<i>I'm going home.</i>

17:57.118 --> 17:59.412
I may not be
a "Forged in Fire" champion,

17:59.412 --> 18:02.331
<i>but I have this great family</i>
<i>waiting for me at home.</i>

18:02.331 --> 18:03.874
I'll always be a winner
to them.

18:03.874 --> 18:06.502
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:06.502 --> 18:08.504
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations.

18:08.504 --> 18:10.381
You've made it to round two,
and now that those blades

18:10.381 --> 18:12.008
have been tempered,
it's time to turn them

18:12.008 --> 18:13.259
into fully‐functioning knives

18:13.259 --> 18:14.885
by attaching handles to 'em.

18:14.885 --> 18:16.095
<i>You must also include</i>

18:16.095 --> 18:19.473
<i>a mosaic pin in your handles.</i>

18:19.473 --> 18:21.392
After this round, we'll be
testing your blades

18:21.392 --> 18:24.604
for strength and durability
in a pipe chop

18:24.604 --> 18:25.688
and for edge retention

18:25.688 --> 18:27.398
in a fish filet.

18:27.398 --> 18:29.942
Good luck.
Your three hours starts now.

18:29.942 --> 18:31.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:31.652 --> 18:34.030
Well, here in round two,
we've asked them to add handles

18:34.030 --> 18:35.406
with mosaic pins.

18:35.406 --> 18:38.326
Mike and John
had relatively few flaws

18:38.326 --> 18:39.952
coming out of round one.

18:39.952 --> 18:43.914
Meanwhile, Daniel,
this guy's way under

18:43.914 --> 18:46.125
the power curve right now.

18:46.125 --> 18:48.878
<i>‐ The judges had a lot to say</i>
<i>about my blade.</i>

18:48.878 --> 18:50.921
There's mild steel
all over my billet.

18:50.921 --> 18:52.548
I have no idea where it is.

18:52.548 --> 18:55.343
I'm trying to find where
the file digs in,

18:55.343 --> 18:57.053
and that'll be the soft metal.

18:57.053 --> 18:59.430
‐ What Daniel should do
is clean that blade off

18:59.430 --> 19:01.057
and dip in the acid,
and really identify

19:01.057 --> 19:03.017
where that hardenable steel is.

19:03.017 --> 19:05.478
‐ Yeah, 'cause that mild steel
will just be a ghostly white.

19:05.478 --> 19:09.440
‐ At the grinder, I'm trying to
get rid of some delaminations

19:09.440 --> 19:11.233
and soft steel.

19:11.233 --> 19:13.986
There's just so much
I have left to do,

19:13.986 --> 19:15.446
<i>and it's taking me</i>
<i>way too long.</i>

19:15.446 --> 19:18.074
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:18.074 --> 19:21.369
‐ My two main priorities
are to get rid of that warp

19:21.369 --> 19:23.871
<i>and to work</i>
<i>on that finger well.</i>

19:23.871 --> 19:26.999
<i>I'm gonna try to get rid</i>
<i>of the warp just by grinding,</i>

19:26.999 --> 19:28.626
<i>so I'm gonna put it in</i>
<i>the acid etch</i>

19:28.626 --> 19:32.505
<i>just to let me know</i>
<i>where my steel is.</i>

19:32.505 --> 19:34.965
<i>The acid‐‐it darkens</i>
<i>the hardenable steel</i>

19:34.965 --> 19:37.635
<i>more than the mild steel.</i>

19:37.635 --> 19:41.472
Ben thought that this was
a little thin for his hand,

19:41.472 --> 19:44.016
so I'm gonna just put a bead
of weld on the bottom

19:44.016 --> 19:46.185
<i>of this handle and try</i>
<i>to widen that finger well</i>

19:46.185 --> 19:47.728
<i>up a little bit.</i>

19:47.728 --> 19:49.855
<i>I'm gonna clamp this</i>
<i>to my blade</i>

19:49.855 --> 19:51.607
<i>to keep any heat that I create</i>

19:51.607 --> 19:54.068
from welding from traveling
down my cutting edge

19:54.068 --> 19:56.570
and ruining my temper.

19:56.570 --> 19:58.197
<i>It's like a heat shield,</i>
<i>basically,</i>

19:58.197 --> 20:01.575
<i>for the rest of the blade.</i>

20:01.575 --> 20:03.744
<i>‐ My first priority is to cut</i>
<i>the tang down.</i>

20:03.744 --> 20:06.414
What I need to do is cut off
an inch

20:06.414 --> 20:09.291
<i>within the last third</i>
<i>of the tang,</i>

20:09.291 --> 20:11.502
<i>because I want there to be</i>
<i>a swell</i>

20:11.502 --> 20:14.380
<i>so that the knife won't slip</i>
<i>out of your hand.</i>

20:14.380 --> 20:18.050
‐ Welding.
‐ Come on, baby.

20:18.050 --> 20:20.261
<i>If I don't get a good weld</i>
<i>on this,</i>

20:20.261 --> 20:23.305
there's a chance when it's used
in the pipe test

20:23.305 --> 20:25.558
that it could crack off.

20:25.558 --> 20:27.435
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:27.435 --> 20:29.437
<i>‐ Well, right now, I'm getting</i>
<i>a little frustrated</i>

20:29.437 --> 20:31.814
<i>because I can't drill</i>
<i>through my tang.</i>

20:31.814 --> 20:35.443
‐ [singing] ♪ More of the same
squealing noises from Mike ♪

20:35.443 --> 20:36.610
‐ [laughing]

20:36.610 --> 20:37.778
‐ You're laughing up there,

20:37.778 --> 20:40.072
but it ain't that funny.

20:40.072 --> 20:42.116
‐ What did you make that tang
out of, brother?

20:42.116 --> 20:44.452
‐ Yeah, the tang shouldn't have
been too hard,

20:44.452 --> 20:46.454
but apparently, it is.

20:46.454 --> 20:50.583
So I'm gonna sharpen a bit
and see if that works.

20:50.583 --> 20:52.084
I was in a really good spot,

20:52.084 --> 20:54.920
but this is putting me behind.

20:54.920 --> 20:56.797
‐ There we go.
‐ There's a hole!

20:56.797 --> 20:58.382
[applause]

20:58.382 --> 20:59.633
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:59.633 --> 21:01.135
<i>‐ I just shorten my handle,</i>

21:01.135 --> 21:02.887
<i>and then I gotta get over</i>
<i>and make</i>

21:02.887 --> 21:06.265
a mosaic pin that I've never
done before in my life.

21:06.265 --> 21:09.310
‐ John's putting a lot of his
weight into this drill press.

21:09.310 --> 21:11.312
‐ We have tungsten carbide
drill bits

21:11.312 --> 21:12.938
that cut pretty hard stuff.
‐ Okay.

21:12.938 --> 21:14.774
‐ The trick to them is
you have to operate them

21:14.774 --> 21:16.400
at a very high
rotational speed

21:16.400 --> 21:17.318
and not a lot of pressure.

21:19.445 --> 21:21.322
‐ Soon as you bear into
a tungsten carbide bit,

21:21.322 --> 21:22.656
it just shatters.

21:22.656 --> 21:24.241
[bit shattering]

21:24.241 --> 21:25.993
‐ Oh, [bleep], I broke it.

21:25.993 --> 21:27.787
‐ Oh, my G‐‐
Oh, my God!

21:27.787 --> 21:31.916
<i>[dramatic rock music]</i>

21:31.916 --> 21:33.667
‐ Cutting a hole
through hardened steel

21:33.667 --> 21:35.961
is a big time deal.
I broke my bit off‐‐

21:35.961 --> 21:37.838
<i>pure carbide.</i>
<i>It was stuck in there.</i>

21:37.838 --> 21:39.840
You're not gonna drill through
it with another drill.

21:39.840 --> 21:42.802
<i>I look and see that there's</i>
<i>a little, tiny hole</i>

21:42.802 --> 21:44.470
<i>sticking through.</i>

21:44.470 --> 21:47.932
The carbide bit started
through the other side.

21:47.932 --> 21:50.976
<i>So I grab a chisel,</i>
<i>and I start tapping</i>

21:50.976 --> 21:52.603
<i>on that carbide bit,</i>

21:52.603 --> 21:55.564
<i>and luckily, it comes out.</i>

21:55.564 --> 21:58.484
Now I'm back in business.

21:58.484 --> 22:00.820
‐ Bladesmiths!
You have just 60 minutes

22:00.820 --> 22:02.321
remaining to finish your work!

22:02.321 --> 22:04.323
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:04.323 --> 22:07.326
<i>‐ In order to get my handle</i>
<i>onto my tang,</i>

22:07.326 --> 22:09.495
I'm gonna do
a burn‐through technique.

22:09.495 --> 22:12.456
<i>A burn‐through is where you</i>
<i>heat up the tang</i>

22:12.456 --> 22:15.334
<i>to a red‐hot heat.</i>

22:15.334 --> 22:19.171
And then you take the handle,
and you shove it on.

22:19.171 --> 22:20.965
<i>You're expecting smoke.</i>

22:20.965 --> 22:22.550
Fire's not normal.

22:22.550 --> 22:23.968
‐ Don't know that
I've ever seen

22:23.968 --> 22:25.636
a really successful
burn‐through.

22:25.636 --> 22:27.680
‐ Well, it's obviously looking
like Daniel's not having

22:27.680 --> 22:29.181
success right now,
'cause he's trying

22:29.181 --> 22:30.683
to change his strategy.

22:30.683 --> 22:32.893
‐ So the new plan is to cut it
in half,

22:32.893 --> 22:34.979
uh, epoxy it,

22:34.979 --> 22:36.814
and stick it together.

22:36.814 --> 22:38.357
<i>‐ Daniel went down</i>
<i>a rabbit hole</i>

22:38.357 --> 22:41.402
<i>trying to make a hidden tang</i>
<i>design.</i>

22:41.402 --> 22:43.946
This is gonna be a mad dash
for Daniel, man.

22:43.946 --> 22:45.865
<i>‐ I wasted a ton of time</i>

22:45.865 --> 22:47.658
<i>trying to do</i>
<i>this burn‐through</i>

22:47.658 --> 22:51.370
when I could have just started
with two pieces of wood

22:51.370 --> 22:53.831
from the get‐go.

22:53.831 --> 22:55.291
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:55.291 --> 22:56.709
‐ There is a thought that I'm
gonna make

22:56.709 --> 22:58.502
a beautiful mosaic pin.

22:58.502 --> 23:00.713
I stop that foolish idea

23:00.713 --> 23:02.673
<i>'cause it doesn't need</i>
<i>to look beautiful.</i>

23:02.673 --> 23:05.551
<i>It just needs to be</i>
<i>a mosaic pin.</i>

23:05.551 --> 23:08.262
‐ What should a good mosaic pin
look like?

23:08.262 --> 23:09.889
‐ At least for me,
it's aesthetics.

23:09.889 --> 23:11.515
So, symmetry‐‐
whatever you do,

23:11.515 --> 23:13.058
just make it look symmetrical.

23:13.058 --> 23:14.643
It looks good.

23:14.643 --> 23:17.146
<i>‐ I'm moving on to placing</i>
<i>the pins in.</i>

23:17.146 --> 23:18.230
<i>And before you know it,</i>

23:18.230 --> 23:19.189
I'm working on the sides

23:19.189 --> 23:20.399
<i>of the scales.</i>

23:20.399 --> 23:21.567
<i>I'm thinning them out</i>

23:21.567 --> 23:22.568
<i>and putting a good texture in.</i>

23:22.568 --> 23:26.071
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:26.071 --> 23:28.616
<i>‐ The more I'm grinding,</i>
<i>the more I'm seeing</i>

23:28.616 --> 23:33.245
<i>that my handle scale</i>
<i>isn't tight against my tang.</i>

23:33.245 --> 23:35.456
The last thing I need is
for one of the handle scales

23:35.456 --> 23:38.083
to pop off during testing,

23:38.083 --> 23:39.752
<i>so I'm gonna have</i>
<i>to fill this in</i>

23:39.752 --> 23:41.420
<i>with some epoxy.</i>

23:41.420 --> 23:43.255
<i>This time, I used a thin wire</i>

23:43.255 --> 23:44.715
<i>that I used out of‐‐</i>

23:44.715 --> 23:46.216
<i>for my mosaic pin</i>

23:46.216 --> 23:47.801
<i>to sort of push the epoxy</i>

23:47.801 --> 23:49.887
<i>down into the cracks.</i>

23:49.887 --> 23:51.889
‐ Ten minutes, bladesmiths!

23:51.889 --> 23:55.100
<i>‐ Everything, absolutely</i>
<i>everything, has taken me</i>

23:55.100 --> 23:57.269
<i>much longer than it</i>
<i>should have.</i>

23:57.269 --> 23:58.771
<i>The biggest concern right now</i>

23:58.771 --> 24:01.273
<i>is getting all</i>
<i>the parameters in.</i>

24:01.273 --> 24:02.775
I'm running out of time.

24:02.775 --> 24:04.526
<i>‐ He hasn't sharpened</i>
<i>his blade,</i>

24:04.526 --> 24:08.113
and his handle is just
incomplete all the way around.

24:08.113 --> 24:09.573
‐ Yeah, it's glued up.

24:09.573 --> 24:12.117
‐ 36 grit it, man.

24:12.117 --> 24:15.120
‐ He's got a pretty aggressive
belt, but it's not a new belt.

24:15.120 --> 24:17.289
‐ No. It's the same belt
he's had this whole round.

24:17.289 --> 24:19.124
‐ The entire time.
‐ Yeah.

24:19.124 --> 24:22.795
<i>‐ The pressure's on.</i>
<i>The glue isn't fully set.</i>

24:22.795 --> 24:25.673
‐ Ten! Nine! Eight!

24:25.673 --> 24:28.300
Seven! Six! Five!

24:28.300 --> 24:31.303
Four! Three! Two!

24:31.303 --> 24:34.264
One! Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing.

24:34.264 --> 24:37.309
Drop your tools. Pull your
blade out of that acid‐etch.

24:37.309 --> 24:38.310
‐ [laughs]

24:38.310 --> 24:39.645
‐ Good job. [inaudible]

24:39.645 --> 24:41.063
‐ This second round
of competition

24:41.063 --> 24:42.898
is over.

24:42.898 --> 24:45.442
<i>‐ This is not how I expected</i>
<i>this round to go.</i>

24:45.442 --> 24:48.445
I expected to have

24:48.445 --> 24:54.284
<i>a nice, finished blade</i>
<i>and a really pretty handle.</i>

24:54.284 --> 24:57.496
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to the strength test.

24:57.496 --> 24:59.331
To test of strength
and durability of your edge,

24:59.331 --> 25:01.458
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

25:01.458 --> 25:04.628
I'm gonna attempt to crush
these copper pipes.

25:04.628 --> 25:06.296
Mike, you're up. You ready?

25:06.296 --> 25:07.840
‐ I was born ready.

25:07.840 --> 25:09.508
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:09.508 --> 25:11.510
<i>You just never know</i>
<i>what could happen.</i>

25:11.510 --> 25:13.137
<i>Ben could chop into that pipe</i>

25:13.137 --> 25:15.014
<i>and my blade could break</i>
<i>in half,</i>

25:15.014 --> 25:17.725
and I could be going home.

25:17.725 --> 25:24.732
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:32.865 --> 25:35.492
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:35.492 --> 25:37.703
‐ Well, Mike, your edge
held up beautifully.

25:37.703 --> 25:40.205
There's no deformation
of any kind.

25:40.205 --> 25:42.124
The only real issue
I had with it

25:42.124 --> 25:45.377
is that the handle
is a little round,

25:45.377 --> 25:47.212
and that did make it
twist in my hand.

25:47.212 --> 25:49.048
On one of the strikes,
I had to double down

25:49.048 --> 25:50.591
and grab a little bit tighter.

25:50.591 --> 25:51.884
But, well done.

25:51.884 --> 25:52.926
‐ Thank you.

25:52.926 --> 25:54.053
‐ John, you're up next.

25:54.053 --> 25:56.889
‐ Let's do it.

25:56.889 --> 26:00.225
<i>After seeing how well</i>
<i>Mike's blade has done,</i>

26:00.225 --> 26:02.561
I only hope that
I can come close

26:02.561 --> 26:04.229
<i>to what his blade did.</i>

26:04.229 --> 26:11.236
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:12.446 --> 26:16.033
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:16.033 --> 26:17.701
[exhales]

26:17.701 --> 26:20.245
‐ John, your edge
held up beautifully.

26:20.245 --> 26:22.372
The only way I would know that
this actually ever even

26:22.372 --> 26:25.793
hit a copper pipe is the smear
of copper on the sides.

26:25.793 --> 26:28.420
It's light, it's fast,
it's fun to swing‐‐

26:28.420 --> 26:30.964
nice job.
‐ Thank you.

26:30.964 --> 26:33.258
‐ Daniel, you're up.
How you feeling?

26:33.258 --> 26:35.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:35.302 --> 26:36.970
‐ Discouraged.

26:36.970 --> 26:38.472
‐ Discouraged? [chuckles]

26:38.472 --> 26:41.391
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:41.391 --> 26:44.603
<i>‐ My biggest concern here</i>
<i>is my handle staying on.</i>

26:44.603 --> 26:48.232
The tang is too small, and I
just did not get enough resin

26:48.232 --> 26:50.067
<i>on the inside.</i>

26:50.067 --> 26:54.613
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:54.613 --> 26:55.739
Yep.

27:00.577 --> 27:03.205
‐ Well, Daniel,
this hardly qualifies

27:03.205 --> 27:04.790
to honestly be a knife.

27:04.790 --> 27:07.459
The handle is essentially
a block of wood.

27:07.459 --> 27:11.505
I mean, it's not really
even glued at this end.

27:11.505 --> 27:14.091
Unfortunately, in its current
state, it's not safe to test.

27:14.091 --> 27:18.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:18.220 --> 27:21.431
‐ Daniel, we commend any smith
that walks through those doors

27:21.431 --> 27:23.976
and puts their skills
to the test in this forge,

27:23.976 --> 27:26.645
and you've proven yourself
to be a tenacious competitor.

27:26.645 --> 27:28.814
However, tenacity wasn't
enough today,

27:28.814 --> 27:32.025
and I have to ask you to please
leave The Forge.

27:32.025 --> 27:33.944
<i>‐ I'm really disappointed</i>
<i>that I'm not gonna see</i>

27:33.944 --> 27:36.488
my knife tested,
but I completely understand.

27:36.488 --> 27:39.575
<i>Without a good handle,</i>
<i>a blade is just a paperweight.</i>

27:39.575 --> 27:41.952
<i>I'm going home‐‐</i>
<i>got my head held high.</i>

27:41.952 --> 27:43.787
You live and learn another day.

27:43.787 --> 27:46.498
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:46.498 --> 27:48.000
‐ John, Mike, congratulations.

27:48.000 --> 27:49.334
You've landed yourselves
in the final round

27:49.334 --> 27:50.419
of this competition.

27:50.419 --> 27:51.670
Now we're sending you back

27:51.670 --> 27:52.838
to your home forges to recreate

27:52.838 --> 27:54.423
an iconic weapon from history.

27:54.423 --> 27:56.508
That weapon is...

27:56.508 --> 27:59.011
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:59.011 --> 28:00.554
The Greek kopis.

28:02.347 --> 28:04.683
<i>Dating to</i>
<i>the 6th century B. C.,</i>

28:04.683 --> 28:07.853
<i>the kopis was the curved sword</i>
<i>of the Greek cavalry.</i>

28:07.853 --> 28:09.980
<i>Similar in shape</i>
<i>to the modern kukri,</i>

28:09.980 --> 28:11.648
<i>this large, inward‐bent sword</i>

28:11.648 --> 28:13.901
<i>carries most of its weight</i>
<i>near the tip,</i>

28:13.901 --> 28:16.069
<i>allowing for powerful</i>
<i>downward cuts.</i>

28:16.069 --> 28:17.529
[blade swishing]

28:17.529 --> 28:19.364
<i>The weapon was so ferocious,</i>

28:19.364 --> 28:20.866
<i>it was capable of hacking</i>
<i>limbs off an enemy</i>

28:20.866 --> 28:23.201
<i>with a single swing.</i>
[blade chops]

28:23.201 --> 28:24.870
<i>The Greek cavalry</i>
<i>soon dominated</i>

28:24.870 --> 28:26.538
<i>the ancient world,</i>
<i>reaching its zenith</i>

28:26.538 --> 28:28.874
<i>under the leadership</i>
<i>of military legend</i>

28:28.874 --> 28:30.208
<i>Alexander the Great,</i>

28:30.208 --> 28:32.002
<i>who we see wielding a kopis</i>

28:32.002 --> 28:34.212
<i>as he rides to victory</i>
<i>in the film "Alexander."</i>

28:34.212 --> 28:36.340
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:36.340 --> 28:38.884
Your blades must fall within
the following parameters.

28:38.884 --> 28:42.262
The length of the blade must
be between 17 and 20 inches.

28:42.262 --> 28:44.806
You must include a fuller
on both sides of the blade.

28:44.806 --> 28:47.392
You must also include a guard,
an animal head pommel,

28:47.392 --> 28:50.354
and a connection between
the pommel and guard.

28:50.354 --> 28:52.105
<i>‐ Well, one of the things</i>
<i>that scares me the most</i>

28:52.105 --> 28:53.732
<i>is trying to make a pommel</i>

28:53.732 --> 28:55.567
that is in the shape
of an animal head.

28:55.567 --> 28:57.527
<i>I've never done any kind</i>
<i>of sculpturing,</i>

28:57.527 --> 28:59.404
<i>so this is an unknown for me.</i>

28:59.404 --> 29:01.239
We'll see what happens.

29:01.239 --> 29:03.241
‐ Bladesmiths, you'll have
five days at your home forges

29:03.241 --> 29:04.910
in which to complete
this challenge.

29:04.910 --> 29:06.244
At the end of those five days,

29:06.244 --> 29:08.872
you'll return and present
your kopises

29:08.872 --> 29:10.749
to our panel of expert judges,

29:10.749 --> 29:12.584
and after they've thoroughly
tested the hell out of them,

29:12.584 --> 29:14.378
they'll declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

29:14.378 --> 29:16.088
who leaves here with a check

29:16.088 --> 29:17.589
for $10,000.

29:17.589 --> 29:18.882
Good luck, bladesmiths.

29:18.882 --> 29:20.300
We'll see you in five days.

29:20.300 --> 29:21.760
‐ Good luck.
‐ Good luck.

29:21.760 --> 29:23.720
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:23.720 --> 29:26.223
<i>‐ Feels great to be back</i>
<i>in my home forge.</i>

29:26.223 --> 29:28.100
I'm excited to get started.

29:28.100 --> 29:29.601
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:29.601 --> 29:30.936
<i>It's day one.</i>
<i>I'm gonna be making</i>

29:30.936 --> 29:33.105
<i>my Damascus billet.</i>

29:33.105 --> 29:35.399
<i>It's welded up, ready to go.</i>

29:35.399 --> 29:38.110
Doing a Damascus blade could be
a little risky

29:38.110 --> 29:40.529
as far as delaminations,

29:40.529 --> 29:43.073
<i>but I think the wow factor</i>
<i>at the end,</i>

29:43.073 --> 29:44.574
<i>it'll be worthwhile doing.</i>

29:44.574 --> 29:46.118
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:46.118 --> 29:50.288
I'm gonna do a wrap
or a San Mai construction.

29:50.288 --> 29:52.374
My Damascus is on the outside.

29:52.374 --> 29:54.876
There's a solid layer
of 15N20,

29:54.876 --> 29:59.715
and then down the center
is one solid piece of 5160.

29:59.715 --> 30:01.591
It should be really pretty

30:01.591 --> 30:03.260
<i>and tough.</i>

30:03.260 --> 30:05.303
But this handle does have me
a little concerned.

30:05.303 --> 30:07.180
<i>That's gonna be</i>
<i>my main obstacle</i>

30:07.180 --> 30:09.474
with this sword‐‐is getting
the handle just right

30:09.474 --> 30:11.810
<i>so that it fits your hand</i>
<i>just right.</i>

30:11.810 --> 30:13.103
Time to quit.

30:13.103 --> 30:14.980
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:14.980 --> 30:17.566
<i>‐ I'm back at the home forge</i>
<i>and getting ready to go.</i>

30:17.566 --> 30:20.777
<i>And this entire piece is going</i>
<i>to be made out of Damascus</i>

30:20.777 --> 30:24.281
with an integral guard
and an integral pommel

30:24.281 --> 30:26.283
built into it, so...

30:26.283 --> 30:28.285
without further ado,
here we go.

30:28.285 --> 30:30.746
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:30.746 --> 30:33.999
If I at the end of day have
a rough shape of a sword,

30:33.999 --> 30:37.002
<i>I'll be really happy.</i>

30:37.002 --> 30:38.837
I set the welds.
Everything looks good.

30:38.837 --> 30:40.297
I'm drawing it out.

30:40.297 --> 30:42.174
<i>It's 30 layers right now.</i>

30:42.174 --> 30:45.302
<i>I'm gonna cut it</i>
<i>into sections, probably three,</i>

30:45.302 --> 30:49.014
<i>to have a layer count</i>
<i>of about 90.</i>

30:49.014 --> 30:50.640
Okay, we got a long way to go.

30:50.640 --> 30:51.933
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:51.933 --> 30:53.852
‐ It's day two.
I have to make

30:53.852 --> 30:55.520
some fullering dies
for this blade.

30:55.520 --> 30:56.980
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:56.980 --> 30:58.857
This is the bottom section

30:58.857 --> 31:00.192
of a railroad track.

31:00.192 --> 31:02.194
<i>Have to round the top off</i>

31:02.194 --> 31:04.029
<i>to get the right shape</i>
<i>that I want.</i>

31:06.156 --> 31:08.867
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:08.867 --> 31:11.036
The fuller lines
are really clean,

31:11.036 --> 31:12.537
symmetrical‐‐

31:12.537 --> 31:14.081
<i>it's exactly</i>
<i>what I was hoping for.</i>

31:14.081 --> 31:15.499
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:15.499 --> 31:17.542
<i>‐ Just started day three.</i>

31:17.542 --> 31:20.378
We're gonna work on the guard
and the pommel.

31:20.378 --> 31:21.963
<i>Got a lot of work to do.</i>

31:21.963 --> 31:23.548
<i>It's gonna be a lot</i>
<i>of detailed work.</i>

31:23.548 --> 31:25.217
<i>It's gonna be slow.</i>

31:25.217 --> 31:28.345
I feel like a dentist.

31:28.345 --> 31:31.515
<i>And then I've got</i>
<i>to quench the blade.</i>

31:31.515 --> 31:34.810
Everything that I've done
since I've picked up a hammer,

31:34.810 --> 31:37.562
<i>is coming down</i>
<i>to this point.</i>

31:37.562 --> 31:40.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:40.190 --> 31:42.692
I hope that this works out.

31:42.692 --> 31:44.444
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:44.444 --> 31:46.571
<i>It's a little bit bent.</i>

31:46.571 --> 31:48.698
<i>I can straighten</i>
<i>this blade out.</i>

31:48.698 --> 31:53.078
I have some pallets of wood;
I have an anvil.

31:53.078 --> 31:55.622
We'll see what 220 pounds
can do.

31:55.622 --> 31:58.458
I'm gonna let it sit there
for ten minutes.

31:58.458 --> 32:00.085
I'm gonna let it cool off.

32:00.085 --> 32:02.712
I'm gonna let it form
to that wood and say,

32:02.712 --> 32:04.673
"You're gonna be flat, baby."

32:04.673 --> 32:06.258
All right,
let's see what we got.

32:06.258 --> 32:09.427
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:09.427 --> 32:11.304
It's perfectly straight.

32:11.304 --> 32:12.848
[claps hands]

32:12.848 --> 32:15.058
I got a straight blade!

32:15.058 --> 32:16.476
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:16.476 --> 32:18.145
<i>‐ It's day four.</i>
<i>I'm excited.</i>

32:18.145 --> 32:21.064
I think, basically,
I just have to finish up

32:21.064 --> 32:22.941
<i>my handle today.</i>

32:22.941 --> 32:25.443
<i>I'm gonna pin</i>
<i>these two pieces of brass</i>

32:25.443 --> 32:26.987
<i>to either side of the blade</i>

32:26.987 --> 32:30.490
to hold 'em in place
while I silver‐solder.

32:30.490 --> 32:32.284
Gonna heat up the guard
a little,

32:32.284 --> 32:34.619
let the heat travel up
the blade

32:34.619 --> 32:36.788
and up towards that solder.

32:36.788 --> 32:38.915
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:38.915 --> 32:40.667
<i>I think this sword is gonna</i>
<i>look awesome.</i>

32:40.667 --> 32:43.086
<i>The color combination</i>
<i>with the brass</i>

32:43.086 --> 32:44.588
<i>and the dark handle scales‐‐</i>

32:44.588 --> 32:46.298
<i>it's just all coming together.</i>

32:46.298 --> 32:48.300
<i>I'm really stoked.</i>

32:48.300 --> 32:51.553
But I still have one more piece
to meet parameters.

32:51.553 --> 32:54.306
I need to connect my pommel
to the guard.

32:54.306 --> 32:56.600
This is gonna go through
the horse's mouth

32:56.600 --> 32:59.936
and it's gonna bend in a V

32:59.936 --> 33:02.063
<i>and come down here</i>
<i>into the guard.</i>

33:02.063 --> 33:04.149
I want to make it look
like reins

33:04.149 --> 33:06.109
coming from the horse's mouth.

33:06.109 --> 33:07.360
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:07.360 --> 33:09.779
I like it. That's good.

33:09.779 --> 33:10.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:10.822 --> 33:12.115
<i>‐ This is the last day.</i>

33:12.115 --> 33:14.242
<i>I've got to put scales on.</i>

33:14.242 --> 33:15.327
When your band saw breaks,

33:15.327 --> 33:17.037
you got to improvise.

33:17.037 --> 33:18.163
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:18.163 --> 33:20.457
<i>I have never put scales</i>

33:20.457 --> 33:23.501
<i>on a blade that's got</i>
<i>an integral</i>

33:23.501 --> 33:25.503
<i>pommel and guard.</i>

33:25.503 --> 33:27.797
I just may have made a really,
really big mistake.

33:29.758 --> 33:32.552
<i>My pin doesn't fit right.</i>

33:32.552 --> 33:34.346
So now I've got to make
the new handle.

33:34.346 --> 33:37.515
I'm terrified that I'm
burning the clock here.

33:37.515 --> 33:39.017
<i>I'm trying</i>
<i>to keep it together.</i>

33:39.017 --> 33:40.685
<i>Inside, I'm like,</i>
<i>"You can't stop.</i>

33:40.685 --> 33:42.854
You've just got to get
through this."

33:42.854 --> 33:44.189
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:44.189 --> 33:45.357
<i>It's coming along.</i>

33:45.357 --> 33:47.234
<i>Now I'm feeling pretty good.</i>

33:47.234 --> 33:51.029
Making this kopis was
a really, really tall order.

33:51.029 --> 33:52.530
<i>I feel like I have done</i>

33:52.530 --> 33:54.908
<i>my best work</i>
<i>that I've ever done</i>

33:54.908 --> 33:56.534
<i>as a bladesmith</i>

33:56.534 --> 33:57.869
right now.

33:57.869 --> 34:00.538
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:00.538 --> 34:01.915
It will cut.

34:01.915 --> 34:04.876
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

34:04.876 --> 34:06.294
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:06.294 --> 34:08.046
‐ Bladesmiths, you've had
five days

34:08.046 --> 34:10.632
at your home forges to work
on your finale weapons.

34:10.632 --> 34:12.801
John, how did it go for you?

34:12.801 --> 34:15.762
<i>‐ I made Damascus‐‐</i>
<i>90 layers of 1095</i>

34:15.762 --> 34:18.265
<i>and 15N20.</i>

34:18.265 --> 34:21.726
<i>It's got an integral guard</i>
<i>and pommel.</i>

34:21.726 --> 34:23.728
‐ Mike, tell us about
your blade.

34:23.728 --> 34:27.649
<i>‐ It's a 5160 core</i>
<i>to the blade.</i>

34:27.649 --> 34:31.152
<i>I made 160‐layer Damascus,</i>

34:31.152 --> 34:35.282
<i>and the guard and the pommel</i>
<i>are brass.</i>

34:35.282 --> 34:36.783
‐ Your weapons will now be put
to a series

34:36.783 --> 34:40.620
of three very brutal
and deciding tests.

34:40.620 --> 34:43.248
Up first, Doug's KEAL test.

34:43.248 --> 34:45.583
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
to find out what kind

34:45.583 --> 34:47.419
of lethal damage
your weapon will do,

34:47.419 --> 34:50.005
I will take your Greek kopis
and deliver some killing blows

34:50.005 --> 34:51.923
on this ballistics dummy.

34:51.923 --> 34:53.466
John, you're up first.
You ready?

34:53.466 --> 34:55.427
‐ Ready.
<i>I'm pretty nervous.</i>

34:55.427 --> 34:59.097
There is no way to prepare
yourself for this moment.

34:59.097 --> 35:02.350
<i>I'm just gonna hope</i>
<i>that my blade survives.</i>

35:02.350 --> 35:09.357
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:09.357 --> 35:12.110
‐ Two! Three!

35:12.110 --> 35:14.946
<i>[echoed shouting]</i>

35:14.946 --> 35:16.615
Six! Seven!

35:16.615 --> 35:18.450
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:18.450 --> 35:19.451
<i>[grunts]</i>

35:19.451 --> 35:23.955
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:23.955 --> 35:25.457
<i>[echoed shouting]</i>

35:25.457 --> 35:28.084
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:28.084 --> 35:29.669
‐ Cool blade.

35:29.669 --> 35:31.880
‐ All right, John, let's talk
about your kopis here.

35:31.880 --> 35:35.300
There is a little crack that
goes around the edge

35:35.300 --> 35:36.968
on both sides.

35:36.968 --> 35:39.679
When I saw the tip, I thought
that was gonna be tip‐heavy.

35:39.679 --> 35:41.181
It's not. There's good recovery
with this.

35:41.181 --> 35:42.849
It's a very powerful
weapon, sir.

35:42.849 --> 35:44.851
It will KEAL.

35:44.851 --> 35:46.519
‐ Thank you.

35:46.519 --> 35:48.146
‐ All right, Mike, it's time
to have fun with your blade.

35:48.146 --> 35:49.814
Are you ready?
‐ I'm ready.

35:49.814 --> 35:56.780
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:58.323 --> 36:00.492
<i>‐ [grunts]</i>

36:00.492 --> 36:03.495
Two! Three!

36:03.495 --> 36:06.748
[grunting]

36:06.748 --> 36:13.755
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:15.048 --> 36:18.051
<i>[echoed shouting]</i>

36:20.261 --> 36:22.639
‐ Good job.
‐ Thanks.

36:22.639 --> 36:24.265
‐ All right, Mike.
Let's talk about

36:24.265 --> 36:25.975
your Greek kopis
right here.

36:25.975 --> 36:29.354
It is heavier, but every shot
that I go in there cuts.

36:29.354 --> 36:30.689
You have a sharp edge.

36:30.689 --> 36:34.192
But more importantly, sir,
it will KEAL.

36:34.192 --> 36:36.361
‐ Thank you.
‐ Good job.

36:36.361 --> 36:39.155
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:39.155 --> 36:41.366
‐ All right, gentlemen, it's
time for the strength test now.

36:41.366 --> 36:42.867
To test the strength,
durability,

36:42.867 --> 36:45.370
and overall construction
of your Greek kopises,

36:45.370 --> 36:46.955
I'll be attacking
these two soldiers.

36:46.955 --> 36:48.248
John, you're up.
You ready?

36:48.248 --> 36:50.208
‐ Ready.

36:50.208 --> 36:53.336
They're going to try
to deconstruct my blade

36:53.336 --> 36:55.046
in a very quick manner.

36:55.046 --> 36:57.215
<i>I'm just hoping</i>
<i>it holds together</i>

36:57.215 --> 36:59.467
<i>and doesn't fly apart.</i>

36:59.467 --> 37:06.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:10.895 --> 37:13.940
‐ All right, John, first off,
that small crack we noticed

37:13.940 --> 37:15.859
has not opened up at all,

37:15.859 --> 37:18.194
which is great.

37:18.194 --> 37:20.405
Your blade took
some minor deformation,

37:20.405 --> 37:21.948
a little bit of roll,

37:21.948 --> 37:24.659
but overall,
it's a strong blade.

37:24.659 --> 37:26.244
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

37:26.244 --> 37:28.079
‐ All right, Mike. You're up.
You ready?

37:28.079 --> 37:29.164
‐ I'm ready.

37:29.164 --> 37:31.416
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:31.416 --> 37:34.252
I'm nervous. I'm worried
I have a fairly thin blade,

37:34.252 --> 37:36.087
<i>so I'm little concerned</i>
<i>about warpage,</i>

37:36.087 --> 37:38.006
or that it's gonna bend.

37:38.006 --> 37:45.013
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:46.431 --> 37:50.852
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:50.852 --> 37:52.479
‐ Right, so Mike,

37:52.479 --> 37:55.482
your edge took a little bit
of damage here.

37:55.482 --> 37:59.611
And then up here, it just sort
of peeled a hair off your edge.

37:59.611 --> 38:02.739
But other than that, this blade
is still sharp

38:02.739 --> 38:04.282
all the way down.

38:04.282 --> 38:05.909
Um, it's got some heft to it,

38:05.909 --> 38:07.285
but your handle construction

38:07.285 --> 38:08.620
does make up for it.

38:08.620 --> 38:10.038
But most of all,
it's a strong blade.

38:10.038 --> 38:12.290
Nicely done, Michael.
‐ Thank you.

38:12.290 --> 38:14.083
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:14.083 --> 38:15.460
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

38:15.460 --> 38:17.128
To test the edge
of your Greek kopis,

38:17.128 --> 38:19.130
I will take your weapon
and I will slice

38:19.130 --> 38:20.632
across these rugs.

38:20.632 --> 38:22.175
John, you're up first.
You ready?

38:22.175 --> 38:24.093
‐ Ready.

38:24.093 --> 38:26.679
<i>So Mike and I are in</i>
<i>a horse race at this point.</i>

38:26.679 --> 38:27.972
I hope to finish strong.

38:30.517 --> 38:37.482
<i>‐ And I'm a little conce</i>
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:39.943 --> 38:46.950
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:48.660 --> 38:52.580
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:52.580 --> 38:54.999
‐ All right, John,
the edge here is sharp.

38:54.999 --> 38:57.085
On this last one, not so much,

38:57.085 --> 39:00.463
but as we can see
on the other rugs, it will cut.

39:00.463 --> 39:01.923
‐ Thank you.
‐ All right, Mike.

39:01.923 --> 39:04.342
It's your turn. You ready?
‐ I'm ready.

39:04.342 --> 39:06.845
<i>I'm a little concerned</i>
<i>that with my edge damage,</i>

39:06.845 --> 39:10.306
that it could possibly
hurt me in the sharpness test.

39:10.306 --> 39:17.313
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:26.948 --> 39:29.117
‐ All right, Mike.
First up, the forward weight

39:29.117 --> 39:30.702
that you have
on your blade here

39:30.702 --> 39:33.705
lends itself to do a beautiful
vertical cut.

39:33.705 --> 39:36.583
But on a diagonal cut,
because of the forward weight

39:36.583 --> 39:39.335
being there, it feels more like
a chopper than a slasher.

39:39.335 --> 39:43.548
So it cut in, but it didn't
slice in to control that.

39:43.548 --> 39:46.801
It's a sharp edge,
and it will cut.

39:46.801 --> 39:48.553
‐ Thank you.

39:48.553 --> 39:50.471
‐ John, Mike,
a "Forged in Fire" champion's

39:50.471 --> 39:53.099
weapon should be
elegant in form

39:53.099 --> 39:54.559
as well as function.

39:54.559 --> 39:56.811
Both of you made
high‐performance blades

39:56.811 --> 39:59.731
that did very well
in our weapons tests.

39:59.731 --> 40:02.358
Our next "Forged in Fire"
champion is...

40:02.358 --> 40:04.986
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:04.986 --> 40:06.821
John. Congratulations.

40:06.821 --> 40:08.823
You're the new
"Forged in Fire" champion.

40:08.823 --> 40:11.701
Mike, unfortunately, your blade
didn't make the cut.

40:11.701 --> 40:13.870
Ben Abbott's gonna
tell you why.

40:13.870 --> 40:16.748
‐ Mike, this really did come
down to the finest details

40:16.748 --> 40:17.832
of weight and balance,

40:17.832 --> 40:18.833
and it's for that reason

40:18.833 --> 40:20.043
we're gonna let you go.

40:20.043 --> 40:21.669
‐ I understand.

40:21.669 --> 40:23.296
‐ Mike, I want you to know
that the judges and I

40:23.296 --> 40:25.590
are proud as hell of what
you've turned in, man.

40:25.590 --> 40:26.925
It was a competitive blade.

40:26.925 --> 40:28.343
It really did come down

40:28.343 --> 40:31.471
to the finest details,

40:31.471 --> 40:33.765
but I have to ask you to please
surrender your kopis.

40:33.765 --> 40:35.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:35.308 --> 40:36.517
<i>‐ It really makes me feel good</i>

40:36.517 --> 40:39.145
<i>that the judging was so close.</i>

40:39.145 --> 40:42.148
This competition was
really tough for me.

40:42.148 --> 40:46.861
It tested a lot of new skills
that I hadn't done before.

40:46.861 --> 40:48.780
<i>It was a big win for myself.</i>

40:48.780 --> 40:50.990
It was a great competition
and a great experience,

40:50.990 --> 40:53.242
and I'd do it all over again.

40:53.242 --> 40:55.328
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:55.328 --> 40:57.872
‐ John, congratulations.
You're our new "Forged in Fire"

40:57.872 --> 40:59.540
champion, and that's a title
that comes with a check

40:59.540 --> 41:00.541
for $10,000.

41:00.541 --> 41:02.293
Please present your blade

41:02.293 --> 41:03.962
to the judges.

41:03.962 --> 41:06.172
<i>‐ I'm unbelievably happy.</i>

41:06.172 --> 41:08.383
I'm a new bladesmith,
and it's something

41:08.383 --> 41:11.094
<i>that I want to do</i>
<i>in the future.</i>

41:11.094 --> 41:13.972
<i>To walk into this world</i>
<i>of bladesmithing</i>

41:13.972 --> 41:18.101
and then join "Forged in Fire"
and compete and win it‐‐

41:18.101 --> 41:19.936
it doesn't get any better
than that.

41:19.936 --> 41:23.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>
